<p>The Cocker Spaniel is a different feeding brief from the big retrievers. It isn't a fast-growing giant whose joints you're racing to protect — it's a compact, energetic medium breed whose challenges are <strong>ears, coat and waistline</strong>. Cockers are unusually prone to ear infections, and food allergies are a leading driver: inflammation from a trigger ingredient thickens those long, floppy ear canals and sets off recurrent flare-ups. They carry one of the most beautiful coats in dogdom, which needs omega-3 to stay silky. And they gain weight remarkably easily — with a breed tendency to pancreatitis on top — so steady, lean, moderate-fat growth is the goal from the very first bowl.</p>

<p>This guide is written from experience. Our own dog <strong>Milo is a 12-year-old Labrador/Lurcher rescue</strong> who's wheat-sensitive — we've lived the daily reality of feeding around a food sensitivity, which is exactly the game an ear-prone Cocker owner ends up playing. Below are the UK puppy foods we'd point a Cocker Spaniel owner towards for 2026, ranked and explained, with the ear-coat-weight science that makes a Cocker pup different from a Labrador or Golden.</p>

